Anti-spoofing Kalman filter for GPS/rotational INS integration
Wenwei Liang , Kui Li *, Qihang Li
School of Instrumentation Science and Opto-electronics Engineering, Beihang University, Beijing 100191, PR China

ARTICLE INFO
Keywords: GPS Inertial navigation Kalman filters Rotational INS Spoofing detection

ABSTRACT
The navigation and positioning accuracy of the carrier can be effectively improved through the integrated navigation of GPS and Inertial navigation system (INS). However, signals from GPS satellites are affected by the external environment, which may reduce the positioning accuracy of GPS. More seriously, the GPS receiver may receive spoofing signals, resulting in positioning errors in the integrated navigation. Therefore, an anti-spoofing integrated navigation method is proposed in this paper. The error propagation characteristics of inertial navi­ gation and the prediction estimation value in Kalman filter are used to detect the spoofing. After spoofing detection, credible GPS positioning results are used for Kalman filter as measurements. The method proposed in this paper can effectively improve the accuracy and robustness of integrated navigation. At the same time, it does not need to modify the existing GPS equipment or additional equipment. The effectiveness of the method is verified by simulation and vehicular experiments.

1. Indroduction
Inertial navigation system (INS) [1,2] is an essential navigation component of many carriers such as aircraft and ships because of its independence. However, the error of INS will accumulate gradually, resulting in the decline of the navigation accuracy over time. The rota­ tional inertial navigation system (RINS) offsets the influence of constant and slowly varying gyro drift and accelerometer bias by periodically rotating the inertial measurement unit (IMU) composed of gyros and accelerometers [3], which improve the positioning accuracy of INS. However, due to the influence of unmodulable gyro drift and angle random walk [4], the navigation accuracy will still decline with time. The error of GPS does not diverge with time, so the integration of GPS and RINS [5,6] can effectively improve the navigation accuracy for a long time.
In integrated navigation system, GPS positioning accuracy is affected by many factors, such as clock error, ionosphere error, multipath effect and so on, which has a key impact on navigation accuracy [7]. In addition, the signal strength of GPS is low and its transmission frequency and the signal structure of C/A code are public. Therefore it may also be subject to malicious electromagnetic interference, including signal jamming [8] and signal spoofing. In signal spoofing, the false signal is provided to the receiver to induce the receiver to use the false signal for positioning calculation, so that the positioning result obtained by the GPS receiver deviates from the real value. GPS spoofing can be divided

into forwarding spoofing and generative spoofing. In the forward spoofing, it mainly includes a GPS receiver and a signal transmitter. After receiving the real GPS satellite signal, the pseudo range mea­ surement value is changed by adding delay. Then, the spoofing signal is forwarded to the target receiver after increasing the power, so as to achieve the effect of positioning deception [9]. In the generative spoofing, the spoofing receiver synchronizes with the real satellite signal, estimates the signal parameters of each visible star tracked by the target receiver, mainly including Doppler offset and phase of C/A code, and then generates the corresponding deception signal based on the velocity information and position of the target receiver [10].
In order to mitigate the influence of GPS spoofing, different types of anti-spoofing techniques have been studied [11–14] which can be divided into three levels. The first one is based on the detection of GPS signal, including signal power detection, signal quality monitoring (SQM), residual signal detection and so on [15]. The second level is the consistency check of GPS data, such as clock consistency check, receiving ephemeris consistency check, etc. [16]. The third level is the detection of navigation and positioning. The main method is the Receiver Autonomous Integrity Monitoring (RAIM) [17], which uses redundant satellite data to detect GPS integrity, such as the parity space method based on fault detection and isolation (FDI) [18,19].
In addition, GPS spoofing can also be detected with the help of other navigation and positioning devices. In the GPS/INS integrated naviga­ tion system, the data of INS can be used as redundant information to

