detect GPS spoofing [20,21]. A batch least squares residuals is described to detect GPS spoofing attacks in [22] and a batch implementation of tightly coupled GPS/INS is provided. The simulation results show that the integrity risk meets the requirements during the 8 min simulation. However, the probability of misdetection will increase if the trajectory is measured by the attacker. In addition, the computational burden is also a limitation of this method. C. Tanil et al. [23] proposed an innovationbased spoofing monitor and integrated it into the Kalman filter of tightly coupled GNSS/INS integration. An evaluation model based on Kalman filter is derived to evaluate the performance of INS monitor. The simu­ lation results show that, The rate of misdetection under the error of 10 m remains below 10-9 during 280 s landing approach of B747. The monitor is also applied in loosely coupled integration and proved to be effective in the simulation of 200 s [24]. In addition, the simulation also shows that the loosely coupled integration has better resistance, because it is easier to introduce the GPS spoofing into the filter in the tightly coupled integration, which will lead to the error of IMU biases estimation.
The above studies focus on the detection ability of spoofing in the short term and lack of treatment for long-term spoofing. And the integrity risk increases with the time of spoofing. Under slow and longtime spoofing, the wrong data will affect the estimation of the filter, resulting in detection failure and filter divergence. The sensitivity of the above methods to slow spoofing and the resistance to long-term spoofing need to be improved.
This paper proposes an anti-spoofing integrated navigation method for the integration of GPS and INS/RINS. In the process of integrated navigation, GPS spoofing is detected according to the positioning results of INS and the prediction position information given in the time update process of Kalman filter (KF). When the GPS positioning result passes the spoofing detection, the measurement update process is executed. The main contribution of this paper is to propose a new detection strategy, which can improve the sensitivity to errors, and provide the strategy of the filter under spoofing, which can reduce the impact of error data on the estimation results and maintain the monitoring of spoofing for a long time. Meanwhile, this method does not require any modification to the existing GPS receiver or addition of other equipment.
The rest of this paper is organized as follows. The Section 2 describes the configuration of RINS and the definition of coordinate. In Section 3, a GPS spoofing detection method based on INS and prediction results of KF is proposed. In Section 4, the proposed method is verified by simu­ lation, and a vehicular experiment is carried out to verify the effec­ tiveness of the method in Section 5. The Section 6 draws a conclusion.

