2. Description of INS and definition of coordinate

Firstly, the definitions of INS and coordinate frames are described.

The core component of the RINS is the IMU which is composed of three

gyroscopes and three accelerometers. In RINS, the IMU is installed in the

chassis through the frame structure. Taking a dual-axis RINS as an

example, the IMU is installed in the chassis by two frame structures as

shown in Fig. 1. The IMU is fixed in the inner frame, one side of the inner

frame and the outer frame is equipped with a servo motor to drive the

frame to rotate, and the other side of the frame is equipped with a

grating encoder to measure the rotation angle of the frame.

In RINS, the IMU can rotate continuously driven by motors so that

the integral of bias tends to 0 in the same direction, and the influence of

bias can be suppressed. The coordinate system used in this paper is

described as follows.

The sensitive axis coordinate frame (s-frame) is obtained by making

the three axes of IMU orthogonal after compensating the installation

angles and scale coefficients of the three sensitive axes of IMU. The

O − xsys plane is a plane composed of sensitive axis of the X acceler­

ometer and the Y accelerometer. The coordinate axis O − xs coincides

with the sensitive axis of the X accelerometer and O − ys forms an acute

angle with the sensitive axis of the Y accelerometer. Eventually, the

O − xs, the O − ys and the O − zs form a right-hand coordinate system.

The body coordinate frame (b-frame) is a coordinate system fixed

with the chassis. In this paper, it is selected as the right-front-upper

coordinate system, in which the axis O − Xb, O − Yb and O − Zb are the

pitch axis, roll axis and azimuth axis respectively. The O − Yb coincides

with the rotation axis of the outer frame. When the rotation angle of the

outer frame is 0, the O − Zb coincides with the rotation axis of the inner

frame. After compensating the installation deflection angle between the

inner and outer frames, the coordinate transformation relationship be­

tween the b-frame and the s-frame can be expressed by the following

directional cosine matrix Csb.

